<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-515-924  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 515 924.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computerworld  June 4 1990 v24 n23 pSR9(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>You can't be too rich, too thin or have too much storage. (datastorage in the 1990s.)andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Hallam, Kenneth.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>Desktop data storage needs will grow in the 1990s as microcomputernetworks expand and begin running applications once found only onmainframes and minicomputers.andP;  Storage options already includeWinchester disk drives on network servers, strings of Winchesterdrives on mainframes, jukebox optical cartridges, and off-linetape libraries.andP;  Price resistance has impeded movement towardhigh-capacity desktop storage, but powerful new machines now haveenough memory and software support to run applications demandingpowerful storage systems.andP;  Users can already buy 5.25-inchrewritable optical drives with capacities of up to 500Mbytes perside.andP;  Future storage hierarchies will consist of 4 to 6Mbytes ofmain memory, fast local Winchester drives with 200 to 300Mbytecapacities, 600Mbyte removable optical storage, and access tonetworks with even higher capacities.andP;  Optical storage will makelarge amounts of data available locally and will be removable.andO;Standards will allow common interfaces that lower costs for bothmanufacturers and computers.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Information Storage and RetrievalFuture of ComputingStorage MediaDisk DrivesLocal Area NetworksStorage Capacity.andO;Feature:   illustrationtable.andO;Caption:   Storage story. (table)andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>